kernel_variant.question:
Six heaps contain 2, 3, 5, 8, 11 and 14 beans, respectively.  
On every turn a player must choose exactly one heap and perform precisely one of the following operations (whenever it is legal for the chosen heap size n):

(A) n \to  n - 1 (provided n \geq  7);  
(B) n \to  n - 2 (provided n \geq  6);  
(C) n \to  n - 4 (provided n \geq  9);  
(D) n \to  0   (the whole heap may be taken only when n\in {2, 3, 5, 11});  
(E) split the heap into two non-empty heaps whose sizes differ by any amount, subject to the restriction that neither of the two new heaps is of size 1 or 4  
    (n \to  (a,b) with a+b=n is legal \Leftrightarrow  a,b\geq 2 and a,b\neq 4).

Players alternate; the player making the last legal move wins.  
Should you play first or second, and what is a concrete winning strategy?

